    "content": "Puntland President Said Abdullahi Deni has issued a warning to opposition figures and armed groups operating in the semi-autonomous region. Deni accused the federal government of Mogadishu of mobilizing these forces in parts of Puntland, a move he says threatens regional stability. The statement was made from the regional capital Garowe, where Deni addressed growing concerns over security and political interference.\n\nThe warning comes amid heightened political tensions in Puntland, which has its own government and security forces. Deni's administration has been at odds with the federal government over resource sharing and electoral processes. Opposition politicians in Puntland have previously criticized Deni's leadership, while armed groups have exploited governance gaps in remote areas.\n\nThe Somali federal government has denied claims of mobilizing forces within Puntland, but Deni's remarks highlight a deepening rift. Observers note that such disputes could undermine efforts to stabilize the region, especially as the country prepares for upcoming elections. Puntland has historically been a relatively stable region, but internal divisions and federal-state tensions pose risks.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, this development underscores the fragility of Somalia's federal system and the importance of regional stability for remittances and investment. Puntland is home to major port cities and trading hubs critical to the diaspora's economic ties with Somalia. Any escalation could disrupt these connections, affecting families and businesses abroad.\n\nThe Puntland president has called for dialogue to resolve differences, but his strong language signals that the current situation may require careful mediation. The international community, which supports Somalia's federalism, is watching closely.\n\nRead the original report from Horseed Media here: https://horseedmedia.net/somalia-puntland-president-warns-opposition-politicians-and-armed-groups/423601/",
