    "slug": "mogadishu-man-credits-radio-program-for-boosting-income-through-seedling-sales",
    "summary": "Ahmed Abdullahi Bocoreey, 47, of Mogadishu's Wadajir district, increased his weekly earnings to $80-$100 by selling seedlings and using compost from organic waste. He attributes his success to advice from Radio Ergo.",
    "content": "Ahmed Abdullahi Bocoreey, a 47-year-old resident of Mogadishu's Wadajir district, has turned discarded organic waste into a livelihood by selling seedlings and propagating plants from seeds others throw away. Composting waste materials, he creates nutrient-rich soil to grow a variety of seedlings, which he then sells at local markets. His weekly income now ranges from $80 to $100, sufficient to cover household expenses, support relatives, and pay school fees for two of his children.\n\nBocoreey credits his improved earnings to knowledge gained from regularly listening to Radio Ergo, a community radio station that broadcasts agricultural and entrepreneurial advice. Before applying the techniques he learned, his business was limited and less profitable. The radio program encouraged him to diversify his work, adopt composting methods, and reduce waste, leading to a more sustainable and lucrative operation.\n\nLiving in a densely populated urban area like Wadajir, Bocoreey faces challenges such as limited space and competition. However, he has managed to carve out a niche by focusing on high-demand seedlings and efficient composting. His story reflects a broader trend of urban agriculture in Mogadishu, where residents are finding innovative ways to generate income and improve food security.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, Bocoreey's experience highlights the importance of accessible information and training in supporting livelihoods back home. Many diaspora members seek ways to contribute to economic development in Somalia, and success stories like this demonstrate how simple knowledge transfer can have a tangible impact on families and communities. It also underscores the value of investing in local media and agricultural extension services.\n\nHis success illustrates how small-scale initiatives can create meaningful change, offering a model for others to follow. As urban populations grow, such entrepreneurial approaches to waste management and food production become increasingly vital for sustainable development.\n\nRead the original report from Radio Ergo here: https://radioergo.org/en/2026/07/radio-sews-the-seeds-of-success-for-mogadishu-family-man/",
