    "content": "Mogadishu — Somali police, particularly the Banaadir Regional Police and the Criminal Investigation Department (CID), have intensified operations against individuals accused of spreading content deemed incompatible with Somali social values on social media platforms. Authorities describe the campaign as a measure to ensure that online spaces remain subject to the same legal standards as offline society.\n\nThe targeted individuals are alleged to have posted material that authorities say undermines societal ethics and Somali cultural values. Police officials have stated that social media users are not exempt from the law and must be held accountable for their posts just as they would be for actions in the physical world.\n\nThis move comes amid growing debate in Somalia about the boundaries of free speech and the responsibility of both the state and citizens in regulating online discourse. While the government emphasizes the need to protect social cohesion and national values, critics worry that the crackdown may be used to silence dissent or limit legitimate expression.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, which heavily relies on social media to stay connected with relatives and follow developments back home, these developments raise questions about the accessibility of information. Many in the diaspora also engage in online discussions about Somali politics and society. The new enforcement measures may affect how they interact with Somalis inside the country or use social media to share perspectives.\n\nPolice have not provided specific numbers of those detained or the exact types of content targeted. However, the operation signals a broader effort by Somali authorities to assert control over digital platforms, which have become increasingly influential in shaping public opinion.\n\nThe government has called for public understanding and cooperation, stressing that the campaign is not aimed at curbing free expression but at maintaining a lawful online environment. Observers expect the situation to evolve as officials work to balance security concerns with the right to free speech.\n\nRead the original report from Goobjoog here: https://goobjoog.com/2026/07/10/dowladda-iyo-booliska-oo-adkeeyay-isku-dheellitirka-xorriyadda-hadalka-iyo-isla-xisaabtanka-baraha-bulshada/",
